Eun-ji felt like she was going crazy. As an emergency dispatcher, her day had been a literal disaster. Reports of a massive flood in the south and a landslide near the tunnels had been pouring in since morning. To make matters worse, the city was dealing with localized blackouts and a severe water shortage because the treatment plants were overwhelmed.

"I have to try and remember everything the callers say," she told her friend, Min-soo, as they sat in a quiet pocha after her shift. "The doctors, the police, they all need the info ASAP. If I don't recall everything perfectly, people get hurt. I feel like I'm out of my mind with stress."

She sighed, staring at her drink. "And the worst part? The rain is supposed to keep falling. This crisis will continue for a long time. It feels like there is no end in sight."

Min-soo poured her a fresh glass. "I feel you, Eun-ji. I‚Äôm under a lot of pressure at the international logistics firm too. Dealing with the time difference with New York means I'm basically working 24/7. Sometimes I feel like I'm back in school taking a high-stakes dictation test or a spelling bee, terrified of making one tiny mistake."

"Tell me about it!" Eun-ji laughed tiredly. "The pressure is on the moment I pick up that phone."

"Look," Min-soo said gently. "You managed to knock off work and get here. That's a win. This job is really hard on your body and your mind, so don't be so hard on yourself tonight. You're doing a job most people couldn't handle."

"I hear you," Eun-ji said, feeling the warmth of the soju. "I guess that‚Äôs just how it goes in this line of work. It‚Äôs a bit much sometimes, but sharing this with you helps me breathe."
